Hydroxyurea in patients with SCD followed in Hemope Hospital in Recife, state of Pernambuco
Syckle Disorders (SD) comprise a set of hemoglobin qualitative diseases, in which hemoglobin gene S is inheritated. [1] From these disorders, the most usual one is the Syckle Cell Disease (homozigosis SS) whose patients present organic damage since childhood, resulting of repetive closing vascular episodes. [2] Several studies with adults have presented the effectiveness of using hydroxyurea (HU), whose main effect is the increase of the neonatal hemoglobin (NHb) in patients with SD with little or none side effects. [3,4,5,6] Hydroxyurea is a chemiotherapic agent very known and utilized for treatment of myeloproliferative disorders (MPD) as chronic mieloid leukemia and policitemia vera. HU's main function is blocking the synthesis of DNA by the inhibition of ribonucleotide reductases, keeping the cells in stage S. [1] HU is easy to use, with little toxical effects and with a myelosuppressor easily reverted. The use of hydroxyurea in the protocols of syckle cell diseases (SCD) treatments has begun in the 1980s, in adult patients. Its use was later authorized to be applied in children. [7] Studies with children, performed during many years, has presented similar effectiveness of HU without large side effects. [2,7,8,9,10] Then, this study had as aims, considered a set of cases, evaluating the effectiveness and the tolerabilitity of HU in infants and young adults with SD, and assessing variations of hematological parameters in both age-groups and of values of NHb in infants.
